[1] Germany, Ruegen: Stone marten
Date: Thu 9 Mar 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: AFX via Forbes.com, 9 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.forbes.com/finance/feeds/afx/2006/03/09/afx2582504.html>

German stone marten diagnosed with bird flu
-----------------------------------------------
A stone marten on the German island of Ruegen has been infected with
the H5N1 bird flu virus in what is believed to be a case of the virus
jumping species, the country's national veterinary laboratory said.
The stone marten is a member of the weasel family and is the 1st
animal of this species to be reported as infected with the virus,
said Thomas Mettenleiter, the head of the Friedrich Loeffler
Institute. The virus has killed 3 cats on the same Baltic Sea island.
The cats are believed to have contracted the disease from eating the
wild birds, which brought the most dangerous form of H5N1 to Germany
in mid-February 2006.
The most pathogenic form of H5N1 can also kill humans.
The institute said the infected stone marten was found on the same
part of Ruegen as the cats.
Mettenleiter said that although the case marks the spread of the
virus to a new species, it does not mean that humans are at any
greater risk of contracting it.
"While this find signals that another mammal species has been
infected for the 1st time, the basic assessment of the epidemic
situation has not changed," he told reporters.
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
Chief Scientist
EAI Corporation
Arlington, VA 22203
<jdudley@eaicorp.com>
[The list of mammals reported so far to have been (naturally or
experimentally) infected by H5N1 includes the following 9 species:
Palm Civet (_Chrotogale owstoni Owston_), Domestic cat/feral cat
(_Felis domestica_), Cynomolgus macques (_Macaca fascicularis_),
Ferret (_Mustela putoris furo_), New Zealand white rabbit
(_Oryctolagus cuniculus_), Leopard (_Panthera pardus_), Tiger
(_Panthera tigris_), Rat (_Rattus norvegicus_), Pig (_Sus
domesticus_). For the locations, dates and references for seven of
these, see
<http://www.nwhc.usgs.gov/disease_information/avian_influenza/affected_species_chart.jsp>.
The Stone marten (_Martes foina_, Family: Mustelidae, picture at
<http://www.animalpicturesarchive.com/animal/a5/MKramer-steenmarter-Stone_Marten-on_stone_post.jpg>)
has become the 2nd mustelid in the list, joining its family member,
the ferret. - Mod.AS]
