[3] Germany, Bavaria: wild birds
Date: Thu 9 Mar 2006
From: Thomas Roesel <roesel@lycos.com>
Source: Press release, Bavarian State, 8 Mar 2006 [translated from
German by the sender, edited]
<http://www.stmugv.bayern.de/de/aktuell/presse/2006/87.htm>

The number of H5N1 infected wild birds increases to 8 in Bavaria, Germany
-----------------------------------------------
H5N1 virus was confirmed today [8 Mar 2006] in a dead buzzard in
Wasserburg on Lake Constance (district Lindau), as well as in a mute
swan from the town of Landsberg am Lech, by the Friedrich Loffler
Institute (FLI). The buzzard and the swan were found on 28 Feb 2006
and 2 Mar 2006, respectively. They tested positive for influenza A
virus in tests by the Bavarian Health and Food Safety Agency
(Landesamt fur Gesundheit und Lebensmittelsicherheit, or LGL). Today,
both avians were confirmed by FLI as being H5N1-positive. The total
number of AI-infected wild birds found in Bavaria increases to 8, of
which 5 are already laboratory-confirmed to have the highly
pathogenic H5N1 virus type.
Since 16 Feb 2006, a total of 1666 samples from wild birds have been
sent to the LGL, of which 1383 have been analyzed for the virus. 17
have been found positive for influenza A. These samples are being
further characterized by the FLI. 8 samples were found H5N1-positive,
and the remaining 9 are still under investigation.
A map of the Bavarian locations where H5N1-infected wild birds were
found is displayed at
<http://www.stmugv.bayern.de/de/tierschutz/vogelgrippe/bayernkarte.htm>.
A table (in German) of the current standings for the results of all
samples can be found at
<http://www.stmugv.bayern.de/de/lgl/vogelgrippe/anzeige.php>.
Further information can be found at
<http://www.tierschutz.bayern.de>.
--
Thomas Roesel
<roesel@lycos.com>
[For a picture of a common buzzard, _Buteo buteo_, from Germany, see
<http://www.justbirds.org/Germania/Common%20buzzard.htm>.
Firsthand, accurate ornithological information on this raptor species
found infected in Bavaria, including its candidate prey and suggested
route(s) of infection, will be helpful.
Italy reported to the OIE, on 22 Feb 2006, the identification of H5N1
in a buzzard, _Buteo buteo_; see
<http://oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_30.HTM>.
- Mod.AS]
